X-Spam-Rating: daedalus.apache.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N

Also note that both apache and tomcat has a default setting that force=20=

re-encodes all pages. in tomcat it is the <DecodeInterceptor /> in=20
server.xml, in apache it is a line that says "AddDefaultCharset on" in=20=

httpd.conf. These are applied _after_ any servlet output so it might=20
lead to strange result, be sure to turn off both directives when you=20
test different encoding problems.

Last but not least is the encoding the SQL database was created in. On=20=

DB2 i have to use the right database constructor to get norwegian=20
character support (db2 CREATE DATABASE mydb USING CODESET ISO-8859-1=20
TERRITORY NO COLLATE USING SYSTEM;). Without the correct encoding on=20
the database constructor the database behave strange in sorting and=20
insert/update scenarios.

To be sure to get everything make sure that all steps are using the=20
same encoding, just like you use the same analyzer (perhaps encoding=20
should be a part of a analyzer?!?)

1: create the database with ISO-8859-1 encoding (my favorite)...

	CREATE DATABASE mydb USING CODESET ISO-8859-1 TERRITORY NO =
COLLATE=20
USING SYSTEM;

2: in the indexer force feed lucene with ISO-8859-1 strings:

	String value =3D resultset.getString("fieldname");
	document.add(Field.UnStored("fieldname", new=20
String(value.getBytes("ISO-8859-1"))));=00
	...

3: force encode all queries to lucene in the same manner
=09
	String querystring =3D httprequest.getParameter("query");
	querystring =3D new String(querystring.getBytes("ISO-8859-1"));
	...


mvh karl =F8ie


